# Simplicity and readability

This is a lightweight showcase project—not a production platform. Optimize for clarity over cleverness.

## Default to simple

- Prefer plain functions and small modules over abstractions, factories, or deep inheritance
- One repo, one Next.js app—no microservices, packages, or plugin systems unless clearly required
- Reuse existing domain services; do not duplicate logic for "future flexibility"
- Skip premature optimization, caching layers, and generic frameworks

## Code style

- Names should read like product language: `getAccountContext`, `calculateRiskSignals`
- Keep files focused; split only when a file becomes hard to follow
- Comments only for non-obvious business rules—not for obvious code
- Match surrounding conventions; do not introduce new patterns mid-project

## Scope discipline

- Build what the README and demo need; defer nice-to-haves (Ollama, MCP server, extra accounts)
- When choosing between two approaches, pick the one with fewer moving parts
- If a feature needs more than ~1 day of scope, cut or document as Phase 2

## Tests

- Test behavior that matters for the demo: risk rules, validation, account isolation
- Avoid testing implementation details or framework internals

## Red flags (avoid unless user asks)

- Repository/DAO layers on top of Drizzle for a 2-account demo
- Config-driven rule engines when a plain `if` in `risk-engine.ts` suffices
- Wrapper types around every API response
- "Enterprise" error-handling hierarchies
